{"id":"1412.6350","submitter":"Alvaro de la Cruz-Dombriz","authors":"M. Abdelwahab (U. Cape Town ACGC), A. de la Cruz-Dombriz (Madrid U.),\n  P. K. S. Dunsby (U. Cape Town ACGC and SAAO) and B. Mongwane (U. Cape Town\n  ACGC)","title":"Constraining the gravitational action with CMB tensor anisotropies","comments":"10 pages, 12 figures, 1 Appendix","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc astro-ph.CO hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a complete analysis of the imprint of tensor anisotropies on the\nCosmic Microwave Background for a class of f(R) gravity theories within the\nPPF-CAMB framework. We derive the equations, both for the cosmological\nbackground and gravitational wave perturbations, required to obtain the\nstandard temperature and polarization power spectra, taking care to include all\neffects which arise from f(R) modifications of both the background and the\nperturbation equations. For R^n gravity, we show that for n different from 2,\nthe initial conditions in the radiation dominated era are the same as those\nfound in General Relativity. We also find that by doing simulations which\ninvolve either modifying the background evolution while keeping the\nperturbation equations fixed or fixing the background to be the Lambda-CDM\nmodel and modifying the perturbation equations, the dominant contribution to\ndeviations from General Relativity in the temperature and polarization spectra\ncan be attributed to modifications in the background. This demonstrates the\nimportance of using the correct background in perturbative studies of f(R)\ngravity. Finally an enhancement in the B-modes power spectra is observed which\nmay allow for lower inflationary energy scales.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 19 Dec 2014 14:09:08 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-12-22"}
